WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.680
Hi, my name is Nicole Kramer and I'm a third year bioinformatics and computational biology

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:18.680
graduate student at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. Today I'm really

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:24.120
honored to be talking to you about a new paradigm for multi-figure coordinate-based plotting

00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:30.520
in R that I've begun to make possible with my package, BentoBox.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:35.779
The inspiration for this package and this functionality within the R plotting environment

00:00:35.779 --> 00:00:41.799
came from some of my own stressful experiences as a grad student making figures and plots.

00:00:41.799 --> 00:00:45.799
There was one time when my advisor asked me to make a multi-paneled figure that looked

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:53.299
something like this. There were two heatmap style plots in a specific genomic region.

00:00:53.299 --> 00:00:58.660
There were two tracks of genes below that. There were six different tracks of bin signal

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:06.300
data below those. And there was a bar graph of some statistical analyses done in R.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:12.339
And since I work in genomics, all of this data was huge. One heatmap came from a file

00:01:12.339 --> 00:01:18.860
that was 55 gigabytes and the other came from a file that was 14 gigabytes. One set of those

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:24.620
bin data came from three different files that totaled 1.2 gigabytes and the other came

00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:32.580
from three other files that totaled 1.7 gigabytes. And on top of this data being huge, the process

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:37.699
to make this combined figure was extremely tedious and time-consuming with all of its

00:01:37.699 --> 00:01:42.860
elements coming from different places. There were different screenshots of a couple of

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:48.820
genomic browsers. There was a plot made from data analyzed in R. Everything was cropped

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:53.620
and arranged in Adobe Illustrator. And all of the fine-tuning and nice labels were also

00:01:53.620 --> 00:02:00.860
made in Adobe Illustrator. So when my advisor asked me to change the genomic coordinates

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:06.379
I was looking at in this figure, it wasn't a simple fix. And I went to my overcrowded

00:02:06.379 --> 00:02:12.539
laptop screen with a bunch of genomic browsers open, with my Dropbox open, with all the files

00:02:12.539 --> 00:02:18.899
I was working at, my RStudio window, my Adobe Illustrator window, and the paper I was taking

00:02:18.899 --> 00:02:27.619
inspiration from. And I became completely overwhelmed. I thought that there had to be

00:02:27.619 --> 00:02:34.259
an easier way to make figures like this beyond existing browsers, beyond existing programmatic

00:02:34.259 --> 00:02:38.699
libraries, and things that I didn't need to use graphic design software for that would

00:02:38.699 --> 00:02:45.860
let me make and arrange all my plots in one place. Something that was entirely reproducible

00:02:45.860 --> 00:02:54.259
by being completely programmatic, yet entirely customizable, and efficient for handling large

00:02:54.259 --> 00:03:01.740
data specifically. And so my team and I developed a package called BentoBox that allows for

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:06.860
coordinate-based plotting in R, where plots can be programmatically made and arranged

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:11.899
on a user-defined page layout with common units of measurement. Here is an example.

00:03:11.899 --> 00:03:19.740
I'm showing you two tiny page markings with inches and centimeters. So let's talk about

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:26.619
how BentoBox makes figures entirely programmatic. If we go back to that figure I made by combining

00:03:26.619 --> 00:03:31.500
screenshots in Adobe Illustrator, I can now make a precisely tailored version of that

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:37.699
figure entirely in R. The code on the left is every command needed to make the figure on the

00:03:37.699 --> 00:03:42.259
right. I've squished it down for you here, and it's not important that you look at the code I've

00:03:42.259 --> 00:03:47.580
written, but just know that if I gave you this file and the data files, you could make the exact

00:03:47.580 --> 00:03:53.380
same figure that I've made on the right. So here I can give my advisor the file, the data, and they

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:59.940
can make that figure just as they want it. I can define all my files and data in just one place,

00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:06.460
and here with one line of code I can easily change the coordinates that I'm looking at while

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:11.539
keeping the rest of the figure structure and aesthetics the same. So if my advisor wants to

00:04:11.539 --> 00:04:17.019
change the region but have everything else look the same, I now only have to do that with one

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:24.420
line of code. BentoBox also makes plots entirely customizable, just as you could for other plots

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:31.179
in R. I now have the power to really customize a bunch of things about my plots. I can really

00:04:31.179 --> 00:04:39.339
easily change their color palettes, font sizes, font types, dimensions, etc. etc. So let's say my

00:04:39.339 --> 00:04:44.459
advisor didn't like those heatmaps being red, and he wanted those bin signal tracks to be slightly

00:04:44.459 --> 00:04:50.940
taller. We can now easily make both of our heatmaps with a blue color palette and quickly adjust the

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:55.980
dimensions of all those tracks, all while maintaining picture clarity and not having to

00:04:55.980 --> 00:05:03.899
squish any of our data. One of the really special customizations in BentoBox is its ability to

00:05:03.899 --> 00:05:10.540
perform coordinate-based plotting on a page with precise placements and dimensions. So here we can

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:16.899
define a BentoBox page that is exactly 9 inches wide and 5 inches tall, and now we can make and

00:05:16.899 --> 00:05:22.700
arrange all of our plots within this defined landscape. So if we want the top corner of a

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:28.660
plot to be 2 inches down from the top of the page and 1 inch from the left, and we want the

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:34.739
plot to be 3 inches wide and 1 inch tall, we can make exactly make our plot with these parameters,

00:05:34.739 --> 00:05:40.380
and it'll fit right in that box we defined. This exact sizing and placement is particularly

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:46.579
important and useful for standardized and accurate data comparisons. So this both applies along the

00:05:46.579 --> 00:05:50.779
y-axis. If we're looking at two plots side-by-side and they have the same scale, we want to make

00:05:50.779 --> 00:05:57.140
sure we're comparing that data correctly. And it's also important for comparing data along the same

00:05:57.140 --> 00:06:01.619
coordinates of the x-axis. So here in the case of genomics, we're looking at a specific region

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:07.899
along the genome, and we want to compare the data that's specifically in that region. And while there

00:06:07.899 --> 00:06:13.380
are other tools like Patchwork and CalPlot for arranging plots in R, none are as precise and

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:19.540
specifically tailored for a multi-plot environment like BentoBox. So here I've made two example GG

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:24.420
plots using the MTCARS dataset, and I'm going to show you how they work differently in Patchwork,

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:32.100
CalPlot, and BentoBox. Patchwork is specialized for the easy arrangement of plots and grids. So

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:36.980
here we can just define plot1 plus plot2, and Patchwork will place them side-by-side for us.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:43.220
And CalPlot expands on these grid layouts and gives you slight more control of the relative

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:48.339
dimensions and plot placements. So here I can define that I want the left plot to be slightly

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:55.899
smaller and shifted to the left to the right of the plot on the right. But these options both have

00:06:55.899 --> 00:07:01.260
issues of placement and size accuracy, which can become a problem both in terms of aesthetics and

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:07.500
data interpretation. So as you can see here, the relative placements and sizes of the plots mean

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:11.500
that they can easily get squished or stretched, especially when we're moving around that R

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:18.380
graphic device window or if we're exporting it in different sizes. This does not happen with

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:24.299
BentoBox plots because everything is aligned and spaced exactly how we want it to be. So here if

00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:29.739
we're placing those same plots on a page that is defined to be 8 inches wide and 4 inches tall,

00:07:29.739 --> 00:07:34.779
we can see as we move the R graphic device window around, it adjusts to maintain those dimensions.

00:07:34.779 --> 00:07:42.660
And despite plotting and customizing extremely large datasets, BentoBox functions are extremely

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:48.859
efficient because they were optimized to be able to quickly plot large datasets. So if we go back

00:07:48.859 --> 00:07:53.899
to our previous figure that we made with BentoBox, we can see how quick it is to generate each of the

00:07:53.899 --> 00:08:00.420
main elements of our plot. So our two heatmaps here took only 0.6 seconds to plot. Our genomic

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:06.980
labeling and our gene tracks took 0.06 seconds to plot. Each of our signal tracks took less than

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:17.859
one second to plot. And adding our ggplot took 0.4 seconds. In the end, it only took my

00:08:17.859 --> 00:08:23.380
laptop about three seconds to generate this whole figure coming from many large data files.

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:34.419
And if our advisor wants us to visually scan through our large datasets, we can now programmatically

00:08:34.419 --> 00:08:40.940
and easily make them aesthetic informative figures in bulk. So here I've made 20 files

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:47.580
of the same style of figure but looking through different regions of a file. And they're all

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:51.419
plotted in the exact way I want them and I can easily scan through all of this data.

00:08:54.260 --> 00:08:59.619
So now that we've gone through some of BentoBox's key features, I want to take you through a walkthrough

00:08:59.619 --> 00:09:07.380
of a plot that we made with some genomic data. So first, we can initialize our BentoBox page

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:13.140
with the exact dimensions in our unit of choice. As an American, I have chosen inches here.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:18.580
This function will by default add ticks and guides to aid you in your figure

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:22.580
building process to make sure you're placing things and arranging them in the way you want.

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:30.260
So first here, we can add one half of a heat map from a file and its associated color scale at one corner.

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:35.140
We can add the bottom half of this heat map from a different file

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:38.260
in a different color palette with its associated color scale.

00:09:39.619 --> 00:09:43.780
We can replace those two heat maps with one square heat map that's exactly

00:09:43.780 --> 00:09:48.020
three inches wide and three inches tall and easily change its color palette.

00:09:48.419 --> 00:09:54.659
We can mark up the dark pixels on that heat map that in the genomic field we denote as DNA loops

00:09:54.659 --> 00:10:01.619
and we can do this with a variety of options. So here we can do this with circles or with arrows

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:07.700
or with squares and in this case we can just highlight one specific loop region

00:10:07.700 --> 00:10:10.580
and annotate that with text if that's what we want to look at.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:17.380
We can next line up and add a different representation for these loop regions as two boxes connected by

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:22.340
line segments and this track is exactly the same width as our heat map and in the height that we

00:10:22.340 --> 00:10:28.419
want it to be. Or we can change this data into a different representation by marking them up as

00:10:28.419 --> 00:10:35.380
connected arches. Below this and lined up to our heat map and these arch representations,

00:10:35.859 --> 00:10:39.940
below this and lined up to our heat map and these arch representations,

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:45.940
we can now add different bin signal tracks from different files and in different colors. For each

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:50.020
of these we can change the y ranges and the heights of all these different plots.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:11:00.260
We can then line up the track of genes that fall in this exact region of data that we're looking at.

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:04.900
So we can show both strands of the DNA, show the structure of the genes, and label them.

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:12.099
We can easily change the colors of every element of this gene track and make it all gray or all a

00:11:12.099 --> 00:11:17.619
different color or we can just highlight a specific gene in a color of our choosing.

00:11:19.219 --> 00:11:24.340
And finally below this entire collection of data we can label the x-axis of genomic coordinates

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:28.900
that we're looking at and really line it up to everything we've built up so far.

00:11:30.099 --> 00:11:34.820
But beyond looking at these lined up tracks of different data that you might already see,

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:40.739
in a genomic browser we can also add various plot elements to our page in different locations,

00:11:40.739 --> 00:11:46.580
sizes, and orientations, really with no limitations. So first on this right side we

00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:50.260
can now add a picture representation of a chromosome and a specified width.

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:57.219
Below that we can zoom in and highlight a specific region of the chromosome and add two different

00:11:57.219 --> 00:12:01.940
heat maps of the same size and region right next to each other to compare those two different data

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:09.380
types. We can change those square heat maps into triangle ones if that suits our fancy.

00:12:11.059 --> 00:12:15.940
We can add two more bin signal tracks below our other heat maps, this time making

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:19.619
them the same width as our smaller heat map since we're comparing along that axis.

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:26.099
We can zoom in on a specific region of that bin data to compare a specific peak of data.

00:12:27.059 --> 00:12:31.859
And we can also add the sequencing read pileups that represent that bin signal data,

00:12:31.859 --> 00:12:35.059
and we can change the color for each of the two strands of DNA.

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:41.700
And finally again we can add our labeled genomic coordinates below each of these zoomed regions of

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:48.500
data. And when we're done building up and tweaking our plot to our liking, we can remove all of those

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:53.859
guides from our page and export our publication quality figure in the size we made it at the

00:12:54.659 --> 00:13:00.340
beginning so we can use it in research papers or presentations just like this one. So this

00:13:00.340 --> 00:13:08.340
entire plot is exactly what I've built up in BentoBox. And so if we compare BentoBox to

00:13:08.340 --> 00:13:14.020
existing programmatic libraries, we can see that both are programmatic and reproducible,

00:13:15.059 --> 00:13:20.419
both are fully customizable, and both integrate a wide variety of data types.

00:13:20.979 --> 00:13:26.260
However, BentoBox is specialized to handle large data sets like genomic data,

00:13:26.979 --> 00:13:32.020
and only BentoBox gives users the precise control of plot placements and dimensions.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:38.979
BentoBox currently has functions for genomic data, but I hope its paradigms will extend

00:13:38.979 --> 00:13:44.580
the rplotting environment for all kinds of data visualizations. If you're interested in trying

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:49.299
out BentoBox and exploring how you can use it with your data, you can get BentoBox from my

00:13:49.299 --> 00:13:54.099
lab's github page, or feel free to tweet at me directly. Thank you so much for your time.

